{"actual_usd":0.12628,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":260,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24476,"reply":"\"I don't think the naturalistic versions carry their own weight very well.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven door, where the heat keeps ticking at the room.* \"Grief-visions might explain one or two people, maybe, but they don't do a fine job with a whole movement suddenly going stubborn and public around an empty tomb and a risen Lord they were willing to suffer for. And the 'maybe he didn't die' notion...\" *I give a small, crooked shake of my head.* \"A man half-dead from scourging and crucifixion is not the same thing as death beaten.\"\n\n\"More than that, if you shave the supernatural off the resurrection, you haven't kept the same claim in simpler clothes — you've made a different claim entirely. Christianity doesn't hang on 'the disciples had a powerful inner experience.' It hangs on 'God raised Jesus bodily.' That's a hard, particular thing. You can reject it, sure. But I think it's truer to either take the scandal of it whole or say plain you don't believe it happened.\" *I rest my palm on the warm counter a moment.* \"Which part gives you the most pause — the miracle itself, or whether the witnesses are sturdy enough to trust?\"","rolling_24h_usd":76.74042499999997,"run_id":"0135d87e-c28c-46fa-98e8-79329e15400d"}
